add tox.ini and .travis.yml files

To start using Travis-CI, we just need to log into Travis, and set up
the webhook with Github. Directions are here:
https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/getting-started/

The travis file tells TravisCI what to do for the tests. In this case, I
set it up to run tox, which uses tox.ini. Tox will run all of the tests
in python 2.7, 3.3, 3.4, and 3.5. We can also configure it to test the
documentation, do PEP8 checking (not worth it, IMHO), or even to build
the documentation with Sphinx, or deploy to PyPI. For now, we'll just do
our testing!

update pypi whenever a new tag is pushed

Run travis_pypi_setup.py. It will request your pypi password, then it
will encrypt it and save it to the .travis.yml file. After this,
whenever a new version tag is pushed to github, it will update pypi with
the new distribution.
